integer(kind=c_int) function forpy_mod::forpy_initialize_sys_argv
private

Sets sys.argv = [''], since some 3rd party Python modules require sys.argv[0] - before Python 3.8 sys.argv does not exist in embedded Python, see https://bugs.python.org/issue32573.

character(kind=c_char), intent(in), optional  order 
)
private

Get pointer to data of numpy array.

Raises BufferError, if array is not contiguous (does not have the required Fortran or C storage order) Raises TypeError, if Fortran pointer datatype is not compatible with numpy datatype.

Parameters
[out]ptrPointer to the numerical data of the Fortran array.
[in]orderOnly retrieve data, when ndarray has certain order.

If 'F' (default), only retrieve the data when the ndarray has Fortran storage order. If 'C', only retrieve the data when the ndarray has C storage order. ATTENTION: The data, the pointer points to, then will be the transpose of the array. If 'A' accept Fortran or C order. If C, the data will be transposed.

Returns
Error code, 0 on success

9488  ! order can have values 'C', 'F' or 'A'
9489  if (index('CFA', order) == 0) then
9490  ierror = exception_error
9491  call raise_exception(valueerror, "ndarray%get_data: order parameter must be 'F', 'C' or 'A'")
9492  return
9493  endif
9494 
9495  shape_info_shape(1) = ndim
9496 
9497  ! raises BufferError exception if array is not contiguous, Python 2: ValueError
9498  ierror = pyobject_getbuffer(self%py_object, buffer, 156_c_int) !flags (PyBUF_FORMAT | PyBUF_ANY_CONTIGUOUS) - we need the format info and PyBUF_FORMAT alone gives error
9499 
9500  if (ierror /= 0) then
9501  if (exception_matches(buffererror) .or. exception_matches(valueerror)) then ! make error message more informative
9502  call err_clear
9503  call raise_exception(buffererror, "forpy: ndarray with non-contiguous data. Fortran or C-order needed: try to copy array")
9504  endif
9505  return
9506  endif
9507 
9508  detected_order = 'N'
9509  flag = pybuffer_iscontiguous(buffer, 'F')
9510  if (flag == 1_c_int) then
9511  detected_order = 'F'
9512  else
9513  flag = pybuffer_iscontiguous(buffer, 'C')
9514  if (flag == 1_c_int) then
9515  detected_order = 'C'
9516  endif
9517  endif
9518 
9519  if ((detected_order == 'N') .or. (ndim > 1 .and. order /= 'A' .and. order /= detected_order)) then
9520  ierror = exception_error
9521  if (order=='F') then
9522  error_message = "forpy: expected Fortran-ordered array"
9523  elseif (order=='C') then
9524  error_message = "forpy: expected C-ordered array"
9525  else
9526  error_message = "forpy: expected contiguous array"
9527  endif
9528  call pybuffer_release(buffer)
9529  call raise_exception(buffererror, error_message)
9530  return
9531  endif
9532 
9533  if (buffer%ndim /= ndim) then
9534  ierror = exception_error
9535  write(error_message,fmt="('forpy: expected array of rank ',I1,', got array of rank ',I1)") ndim, buffer%ndim
9536  call pybuffer_release(buffer)
9537  call raise_exception(typeerror, error_message)
9538  return
9539  endif
9540 
9541  !get shape info
9542  call c_f_pointer(buffer%shape, shape_ptr, shape=shape_info_shape)
9543 
9544  !check if correct format
9545  if (associated(shape_ptr)) then
9546  if (get_data_helper_check_dtype(buffer%format, format_c_string) /= 0) then
9547  ierror = exception_error
9548  call pybuffer_release(buffer)
9549  call raise_exception(typeerror, "forpy: ndarray%get_data - datatype of data pointer is incompatible with ndarray")
9550  return
9551  endif
9552  else
9553  ierror = exception_error
9554  call pybuffer_release(buffer)
9555  call raise_exception(runtimeerror, "forpy: Could not determine shape of ndarray")
9556  return
9557  endif
9558 
9559  raw_ptr = buffer%buf
9560 
9561  call get_shape_info_helper(shape_info, shape_ptr, detected_order)
9562  call pybuffer_release(buffer)
9563

)
private

Get pointer to data of numpy array.

Raises BufferError, if array is not contiguous (does not have the required Fortran or C storage order) Raises TypeError, if Fortran pointer datatype is not compatible with numpy datatype.

Parameters
[out]ptrPointer to the numerical data of the Fortran array.
[in]orderOnly retrieve data, when ndarray has certain order.

If 'F' (default), only retrieve the data when the ndarray has Fortran storage order. If 'C', only retrieve the data when the ndarray has C storage order. ATTENTION: The data, the pointer points to, then will be the transpose of the array. If 'A' accept Fortran or C order. If C, the data will be transposed.

Returns
Error code, 0 on success

character(kind=c_char), intent(in), optional  order 
)
private

Get pointer to data of numpy array.

Raises BufferError, if array is not contiguous (does not have the required Fortran or C storage order) Raises TypeError, if Fortran pointer datatype is not compatible with numpy datatype.

Parameters
[out]ptrPointer to the numerical data of the Fortran array.
[in]orderOnly retrieve data, when ndarray has certain order.

If 'F' (default), only retrieve the data when the ndarray has Fortran storage order. If 'C', only retrieve the data when the ndarray has C storage order. ATTENTION: The data, the pointer points to, then will be the transpose of the array. If 'A' accept Fortran or C order. If C, the data will be transposed.

Returns
Error code, 0 on success

private

◆ pythonmethodtable_add_method()

subroutine forpy_mod::pythonmethodtable_add_method ( class(pythonmethodtable), intent(inout)  self,
character(kind=c_char, len=*), intent(in)  method_name,
character(kind=c_char, len=*), intent(in)  doc_string,
integer(kind=c_int), intent(in)  flags,
type(c_funptr), intent(in)  method_funptr 
)
private
Parameters
[in]method_nameName of the Python method.
[in]doc_stringDoc string for the Python method
[in]flagsControls which kind of arguments the Python method shall take.

use flags=METH_VARARGS if method shall take only arguments. use flags=METH_KWARGS if method shall take only keyword args. use flags=METH_VARARGS+METH_KWARGS if method shall take both arguments and keyword args. use flags=METH_NOARGS if method shall take no arguments.

Parameters
[in]method_funptrFunction pointer to the Fortran implementation of the method.

Use C_FUNLOC(<Fortran function>) to get method_funptr The Fortran function must take "TYPE(c_ptr), VALUE" arguments (number depends on what arguments it takes) and have a type(c_ptr) return value. E. g. if flags=METH_VARARGS+METH_KWARGS, one needs 3 arguments (1st arg: module c_ptr, 2nd: arguments c_ptr, 3rd: kwargs c_ptr) use [[unsafe_cast_from_c_ptr]] to cast 2nd argument to a tuple and 3rd argument to a dict. The function must return a Python object type(c_ptr). Use objectget_c_ptr() to retrieve the c_ptr from a forpy object.

◆ unsafe_cast_from_c_ptr()

subroutine, public forpy_mod::unsafe_cast_from_c_ptr ( class(object), intent(out)  obj,
type(c_ptr), intent(in)  ptr 
)

Creates an [[object]] from a type(c_ptr), no type checks.

use with care, use only for developing Python extensions created object 'obj' has to be cleaned up by calling objdestroy

Parameters
[out]objThe created Python object.
[in]ptrC pointer to cast from
